SUMMARY:Why Obfuscation is (still) Needed (more than ever)
DESCRIPTION:This salon series at Indiana University features leading thin
 kers exploring how to build better digital and natural worlds.Beyond the 
 Web / After Analog Speaker Series.  This talk examines data obfuscation\,
  defined as the "production\, inclusion\, addition\, or communication of 
 misleading\, ambiguous\, of false data in an effort to evade\, distract\,
  or confuse". The concept emerged from early interventions such as TrackM
 eNot (2006) and AdNauseam (2014)\, two browser extensions designed to dis
 rupt behavioral profilingŌĆöprojects that were both widely praised and sh
 arply criticized.  The talk revisits this work to explain why obfuscation
  was chosen as a strategy and why these particular designs were pursued o
 ver potentially more effective alternatives. Turning to the contemporary 
 landscape of generative AI and large language models\, where privacy thre
 ats have intensified\, it asks whether new technologies create opportunit
 ies to extend the ethical and practical successes of earlier efforts whil
 e addressing their limitations.About the Speaker  A Professor of Informat
 ion Science and the founding director of the Digital Life Initiative at C
 ornell Tech. Her research spans issues of bias\, trust\, security\, auton
 omy\, and accountability in digital systems\, most notably\, privacy as c
 ontextual integrity. Professor Nissenbaum's publications include the book
 s Obfuscation: A User's Guide for Privacy and Protest (https://mitpress.m
 it.edu/books/obfuscation)\, with Finn Brunton (MIT Press\, 2015)\, Values
  at Play in Digital Games (https://www.valuesatplay.org/vap-the-book)\, w
 ith Mary Flanagan (MIT Press\, 2014)\, and Privacy in Context: Technology
 \, Policy\, and the Integrity of Social Life (https://www.sup.org/books/t
 itle/?id=8862) (Stanford\, 2010). These\, along with numerous research ar
 ticles\, have been translated into seven languages\, including Polish\, C
 hinese\, and Portuguese. She received the 2014 Barwise Prize from the Ame
 rican Philosophical Association and the IACAP Covey Award for computing\,
  ethics\, and philosophy. Professor Nissenbaum has also contributed to pr
 ivacy-enhancing free software\, such as TrackMeNot (http://trackmenot.io/
 ) (designed to prevent the profiling of web search histories) and AdNause
 am (https://adnauseam.io/) (designed to counter profiling based on ad cli
 cks). She holds a Ph.D. in philosophy from Stanford University and a B.A.
  (Hons) in Philosophy and Mathematics from the University of the Witwater
 srand (http://www.wits.ac.za/)\, South Africa.
