LOCATION:GA - Room Number: 3067
SUMMARY:The Spirit\, Shade and Shape of Sasanian Women and Its Impact on 
 Female Images along the Silk Road - a Lecture by Dr. Chen Su
DESCRIPTION:By synthesizing archaeological remains with textual evidence\
 , this lecture explores the multifaceted roles and images of Sasanian wom
 en through the lens of late antique Persian culture. Under the influence 
 of Zoroastrian dualism\, the perception of women in ancient Iran was divi
 ded into two categoriesŌĆöthe "good" and the "evil"ŌĆöa paradox that deep
 ly informed their figures in religious writing\, secular literature\, and
  artistic presentations. This talk will highlight the significant presenc
 e of female iconography across various materials\, including coins\, seal
 s\, metalwork\, and rock reliefs\, tracing how these vibrant artistic dep
 ictions traveled along the Silk Road into Central and East Asia. Furtherm
 ore\, the lecture will examine how specific Sasanian visual motifs and fo
 rmalized patterns left a lasting imprint on the portrayal of women within
  the Buddhist and secular art of medieval China and Central Asia.  Dr. Su
  Chen is a lecturer at Inner Mongolia University and currently a visiting
  scholar at the IAUNRC. She received her Ph.D. from Peking University in 
 2023\, after a year of doctoral exchange studies at CEUS in 2020. Her res
 earch focuses on Iranian history and Sino-Iran cultural exchange along th
 e Silk Road\, drawing primarily on Middle Persian and Classical Persian h
 istorical sources. She has published papers on topics including the urban
  history of the Ilkhanate\, Sasanian social history\, and Persian histori
 ography.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  By synthesizing archaeological remains 
 with textual evidence\, this lecture explores the multifaceted roles and 
 images of Sasanian women through the lens of late antique Persian culture
 . Under the influence of Zoroastrian dualism\, the perception of women in
  ancient Iran was divided into two categoriesŌĆöthe "good" and the "evil"
 ŌĆöa paradox that deeply informed their figures in religious writing\, se
 cular literature\, and artistic presentations. This talk will highlight t
 he significant presence of female iconography across various materials\, 
 including coins\, seals\, metalwork\, and rock reliefs\, tracing how thes
 e vibrant artistic depictions traveled along the Silk Road into Central a
 nd East Asia. Furthermore\, the lecture will examine how specific Sasania
 n visual motifs and formalized patterns left a lasting imprint on the por
 trayal of women within the Buddhist and secular art of medieval China and
  Central Asia.<br /><br /></p><p>  Dr. Su Chen is a lecturer at Inner Mon
 golia University and currently a visiting scholar at the IAUNRC. She rece
 ived her Ph.D. from Peking University in 2023\, after a year of doctoral 
 exchange studies at CEUS in 2020. Her research focuses on Iranian history
  and Sino-Iran cultural exchange along the Silk Road\, drawing primarily 
 on Middle Persian and Classical Persian historical sources. She has publi
 shed papers on topics including the urban history of the Ilkhanate\, Sasa
 nian social history\, and Persian historiography.</p>
