SUMMARY:ACES Horizon Talk: Dr. Charlotte D'Evelyn\, "The Choor Fiddle and
  Sonic Imagination of the Past in Inner Mongolia\, China"
DESCRIPTION:Musical practices of the Mongol people have become increasing
 ly well known around the world\, particularly Mongolian throat-singing an
 d the two-string horsehead fiddle\, morin khuur. Much less is known about
  treasured local fiddle forms in Inner Asia\, such as the ikel from Weste
 rn Mongolia and the choor from Eastern Inner Mongolia\, China. In this ta
 lk\, Professor D'Evelyn explores the important role that the choor fiddle
  has played in Inner Mongolia\, both as part of storytelling ritual in th
 e past and as part of a cultural revival in the present.    Due to histor
 ical ruptures and a growing emphasis on staged performance\, the choor fi
 ddle was largely neglected and transmitted by only a small number of prac
 titioners during the mid-twentieth century. Beginning in the early 2000s\
 , however\, renewed interest in the instrument led many young people to v
 iew the choor as a sonic link to a tradition that predates the establishm
 ent of the People's Republic of China. Drawing on theories of revival (Bi
 thell and Hill 2013) and scholarship on intangible cultural heritage in C
 hina (Tang 2021\; Wong 2019\; Wilcox 2018\; Maags and Svensson 2018)\, th
 is talk examines how the choor functions as a sonic resource for bringing
  the past into the presentŌĆöparadoxically operating both as a uniquely l
 ocal Eastern Mongolian tradition and as a region-wide sonic emblem of Inn
 er Mongolia.      Charlotte D'Evelyn (PhD\, University of Hawai'i at M─ün
 oa\, 2013) is an ethnomusicologist who has spent over a decade studying m
 usic and the politics of ethnicity in Inner Mongolia\, China. Her career 
 in ethnomusicology began in 2002 when she first traveled to China for lan
 guage exchange and began studying the Chinese erhu (two-string fiddle). H
 er interest in this instrument developed into a broader focus on spike fi
 ddles and the music cultures of the Silk Road regions. Her research on th
 e Mongolian morin khuur (horsehead fiddle) led her to Inner Mongolia\, wh
 ere she regularly conducts fieldwork on fiddles and vocal traditions alon
 g the ChinaŌĆōMongolia border. At Skidmore College\, she teaches interdis
 ciplinary courses such as Thinking About Music\, Cross-Cultural Listening
 \, and Global Pop\, and directs both the Chinese Ensemble and the Mongoli
 a Ensemble.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<div><p><span data-olk-copy-source="MessageB
 ody">Musical practices of the Mongol people have become increasingly well
  known around the world\, particularly Mongolian throat-singing and the t
 wo-string horsehead fiddle\, <i>morin khuur</i>. Much less is known about
  treasured local fiddle forms in Inner Asia\, such as the <i>ikel</i> fro
 m Western Mongolia and the <i>choor</i> from Eastern Inner Mongolia\, Chi
 na. In this talk\, Professor D'Evelyn explores the important role that th
 e choor fiddle has played in Inner Mongolia\, both as part of storytellin
 g ritual in the past and as part of a cultural revival in the present.</s
 pan></p></div><div><p>    Due to historical ruptures and a growing emphas
 is on staged performance\, the choor fiddle was largely neglected and tra
 nsmitted by only a small number of practitioners during the mid-twentieth
  century. Beginning in the early 2000s\, however\, renewed interest in th
 e instrument led many young people to view the choor as a sonic link to a
  tradition that predates the establishment of the People's Republic of Ch
 ina. Drawing on theories of revival (Bithell and Hill 2013) and scholarsh
 ip on intangible cultural heritage in China (Tang 2021\; Wong 2019\; Wilc
 ox 2018\; Maags and Svensson 2018)\, this talk examines how the choor fun
 ctions as a sonic resource for bringing the past into the presentŌĆöparad
 oxically operating both as a uniquely local Eastern Mongolian tradition a
 nd as a region-wide sonic emblem of Inner Mongolia.  </p><p>    Charlotte
  D'Evelyn (PhD\, University of Hawai'i at M─ünoa\, 2013) is an ethnomusic
 ologist who has spent over a decade studying music and the politics of et
 hnicity in Inner Mongolia\, China. Her career in ethnomusicology began in
  2002 when she first traveled to China for language exchange and began st
 udying the Chinese erhu (two-string fiddle). Her interest in this instrum
 ent developed into a broader focus on spike fiddles and the music culture
 s of the Silk Road regions. Her research on the Mongolian <i>morin khuur<
 /i> (horsehead fiddle) led her to Inner Mongolia\, where she regularly co
 nducts fieldwork on fiddles and vocal traditions along the ChinaŌĆōMongol
 ia border. At Skidmore College\, she teaches interdisciplinary courses su
 ch as <i>Thinking About Music</i>\, <i>Cross-Cultural Listening</i>\, and
  <i>Global Pop</i>\, and directs both the Chinese Ensemble and the Mongol
 ia Ensemble.  </p></div>
