SUMMARY:REEI Colloquium: "Ukraine's Alleged 'East-West' Domestic Divide: 
 Why Has the Country Survived 2014 and 2022?" with Petro Kuzyk
DESCRIPTION:Since gaining independence in 1991\, Ukraine has often been r
 egarded as a hopelessly divided society and a failing polity. However\, t
 his sticky image of Ukraine does not match the fact that the country has 
 been able to resist both Russia's limited military and hybrid attack in 2
 014 and full-scale aggression in 2022. In this presentation\, Dr. Kuzyk w
 ill address the issue of deluded and manipulated interpretations of Ukrai
 nian domestic 'east-west' differences. He will argue that the alleged 'ea
 st-west' split is overstated\, unstable\, receding over time\, and shaped
  by foreign misconceptions about Ukraine's societal differences as much a
 s by internal political disputes and conflicts.  Petro Kuzyk is an Associ
 ate Professor of the International Relations Department at Ivan Franko Na
 tional University of Lviv (Ukraine). His recent research has focused on U
 kraine's 'east-west' cleavage and its international misinterpretations\, 
 as well as the representation of the country's wartime diplomatic efforts
  in domestic public discourse. During the 2025-26 academic year\, Petro K
 uzyk is a Fulbright Visiting Professor at the Byrnes Institute of Indiana
  University-Bloomington.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<div class="x_elementToProof" data-olk-copy-
 source="MessageBody">  Since gaining independence in 1991\, Ukraine has o
 ften been regarded as a hopelessly divided society and a failing polity. 
 However\, this sticky image of Ukraine does not match the fact that the c
 ountry has been able to resist both Russia's limited military and hybrid 
 attack in 2014 and full-scale aggression in 2022. In this presentation\, 
 Dr. Kuzyk will address the issue of deluded and manipulated interpretatio
 ns of Ukrainian domestic 'east-west' differences. He will argue that the 
 alleged 'east-west' split is overstated\, unstable\, receding over time\,
  and shaped by foreign misconceptions about Ukraine's societal difference
 s as much as by internal political disputes and conflicts.</div><div clas
 s="x_elementToProof" aria-hidden="true"></div><div class="x_elementToProo
 f">  Petro Kuzyk is an Associate Professor of the International Relations
  Department at Ivan Franko National University of Lviv (Ukraine). His rec
 ent research has focused on Ukraine's 'east-west' cleavage and its intern
 ational misinterpretations\, as well as the representation of the country
 's wartime diplomatic efforts in domestic public discourse. During the 20
 25-26 academic year\, Petro Kuzyk is a Fulbright Visiting Professor at th
 e Byrnes Institute of Indiana University-Bloomington.</div>
