BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:IU Hamilton Lugar School
DTSTART:20260413T160000Z
DTEND:20260413T173000Z
LOCATION:The Ostrom Workshop\, 513 N PARK AVE - Room Number: Tocqueville
GEO:39.171057;-86.524959
SUMMARY:Ostrom Workshop | Colloquium: Brandice Canes-Wrone
DESCRIPTION:Bio  Brandice Canes-Wrone is a professor in the political sci
 ence department and the Maurice R. Greenberg Senior Fellow in the Hoover 
 Institution at Stanford University. She is also the Director of the Cente
 r for Revitalizing American Institutions (RAI). During the course of her 
 career\, Canes-Wrone has published extensively the areas of political ins
 titutions\, mass political behavior\, and political economy\, including b
 ooks with University of Chicago and Cambridge University presses and scor
 es of articles in the leading journals of political science. A member of 
 the American Academy of Arts and Sciences and the American Academy of Sci
 ences and Letters\, she has served on the boards of the American National
  Elections Studies\, the Institute for Advanced Study in Toulouse\, and t
 he Presidents and Executive Politics Section of the American Political Sc
 ience Association. Prior to joining the Stanford faculty\, Canes-Wrone wa
 s on the faculties of MIT\, Northwestern\, and Princeton.Title  Campaign 
 Contributions and Self-Reports: How Accurate are Survey Responses Regardi
 ng Donation Behavior?Abstract  Measures of political donation behavior co
 mmonly depend on survey self-reports. In the United States\, the discrepa
 ncy between validated donors according to the Federal Election Commission
  and self-reported estimates has often been over 20 percentage points. Be
 cause campaigns do not have to itemize donors who give no more than $200\
 , it is unclear whether this discrepancy is due to overreporting\, such a
 s occurs for voting. We conduct an original survey of validated donors an
 d the general population\, including items on whether the respondent gave
  above the legal reporting threshold and that enable comparing validated 
 versus self-reported donors. Additionally\, on separate samples\, we cond
 uct a list experiment where the sensitive item is donating. Results sugge
 st that overreporting is significant but drops substantially once respond
 ents are asked about whether they gave above the legal reporting threshol
 d. Furthermore\, although the demographics of self-reported versus valida
 ted donors differ considerably\, policy preferences are relatively simila
 r between the two groups.About the Colloquium SeriesEach Monday throughou
 t the academic year\, speakers share and discuss cutting edge research ec
 hoing the themes of the Ostrom Workshop's research program. Topics range 
 from the governance of space\, cybersecurity\, and data management\, to t
 he environment\, political economy\, and sustainable food science. Presen
 ters are from IU and around the world. Join us at the workshop or over Zo
 om to learn how the Ostrom legacy is evolving today. For more information
 \, see ourwebsite (https://ostromworkshop.indiana.edu/index.html).
