SUMMARY:ą¤čĆčÅą╝ą░čÅ čĆąĄčćčī!/Straight Talk! Russian Language Colloquium
 : "Belarus 101: Crossroad of Europe" with Ilya Silich
DESCRIPTION:This lecture introduces Belarus as a historical crossroads of
 ten overlooked in Western narratives. Through a series of vivid snapshots
 \, it explores unexpected connections from Gothic migrations and Viking t
 rade routes to religious diversity in the Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth.
  It highlights Jewish intellectual life\, Protestant movements\, and mult
 icultural communities\, as well as links to American history\, including 
 migration and industrial exchange. It traces how these legacies shape a m
 odern tension between preserved Soviet legacy like collective farms and K
 GB and a highly developed digital market forced out of the country. The l
 ecture concludes by explaining contemporary authoritarianism\, exiled gov
 ernment in the 21st century\, protests\, political prisoners\, and why U.
 S. engagement has played a tangible role in recent developments.Ilya Sili
 ch is a Belarusian activist-in-exile\, IT specialist\, and former elected
  representative in the digital grassroots democracy initiative "ąĪčģąŠą┤"
  (Assembly) in Brest. He supervised volunteers and monitored elections in
  2020 as a member of civic engagement initiative "ą¦ąĄčüčéąĮčŗąĄ ąøčÄą┤ąĖ
 " (Honest People). Ilya hold degrees in art studies from the Belarusian S
 tate Academy of Arts. He is currently an independent researcher with a fo
 cus on civil society\, political transformation\, and national identity.
