X-SOURCE:IU Hamilton Lugar School
DTSTART:20260430T210000Z
DTEND:20260430T221500Z
LOCATION:GISB - Room Number: 1118
SUMMARY:U.S. Economic Cooperation with Nations in the Middle East and Cen
 tral Asia: Working Towards Regional Stabilities
DESCRIPTION:Nations of the Middle East and Central Asia have emerged over
  the last decade as important partners to the United States both economic
 ally and strategically. Economic ties have expanded with the United State
 s through two-way direct investments\, third country cooperation\, collab
 oration in innovation technologies and supply chain diversifications. At 
 the same time\, the economic integration of these two regions has also in
 creased\, with both state and private investment from the GCC countries i
 nto Turkey and Central Asia. In the geopolitical sphere\, Middle Eastern 
 nations seek to maintain good relationships with China and Russia\, while
  enhancing ties with Washington. Central Asian countries seek to expand p
 olitical and economic links with the United States to diversify from Russ
 ia and China. This discussion will focus on the business and economic tie
 s between America and these regions as they look toward regional stabilit
 y and global economic competitiveness.  &#160\;  Khush Choksy is senior v
 ice president of International Member Relations at the U.S. Chamber of Co
 mmerce. In this capacity\, he oversees member engagement and fundraising 
 across the International Division and its over 30 business councils and p
 rograms. He also leads the Chamber's programs in the Middle East\, T├╝rki
 ye\, and Central Asia.  As the head of International Member Relations\, C
 hoksy is responsible for member services across all the U.S. Chamber's co
 mpanies that are part of its International Division.  As senior vice pres
 ident of the Middle East and T├╝rkiye Department\, Choksy's responsibilit
 ies include oversight of several bilateral business councils and programs
 . Under his leadership\, the Middle East portfolio has expanded to become
  the U.S. Chamber's largest international program and represents over 250
  companies. Choksy also led the effort to integrate the U.S.-India Busine
 ss Council into the U.S. Chamber.  Before joining the Chamber\, Choksy wa
 s a director at Chemonics International. There\, he led teams developing 
 economic ties between the United States and the Middle East. He lived and
  worked in Jordan for seven years\, and also lived and worked in India\, 
 Sri Lanka\, and the U.K. Prior to that\, Choksy worked for the Parsons Co
 rporation. He is a recognized thought leader on the role of international
  business in the global economy.  Choksy received his M.B.A. in strategic
  management from the Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania and
  his B.A.\, magna cum laude\, from Hamilton College. He lives with his wi
 fe and daughter in Chevy Chase\, Maryland.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  Nations of the Middle East and Central 
 Asia have emerged over the last decade as important partners to the Unite
 d States both economically and strategically. Economic ties have expanded
  with the United States through two-way direct investments\, third countr
 y cooperation\, collaboration in innovation technologies and supply chain
  diversifications. At the same time\, the economic integration of these t
 wo regions has also increased\, with both state and private investment fr
 om the GCC countries into Turkey and Central Asia. In the geopolitical sp
 here\, Middle Eastern nations seek to maintain good relationships with Ch
 ina and Russia\, while enhancing ties with Washington. Central Asian coun
 tries seek to expand political and economic links with the United States 
 to diversify from Russia and China. This discussion will focus on the bus
 iness and economic ties between America and these regions as they look to
 ward regional stability and global economic competitiveness.</p><p>  &#16
 0\;</p><p>  Khush Choksy is senior vice president of International Member
  Relations at the U.S. Chamber of Commerce. In this capacity\, he oversee
 s member engagement and fundraising across the International Division and
  its over 30 business councils and programs. He also leads the Chamber's 
 programs in the Middle East\, T├╝rkiye\, and Central Asia.</p><p>  As the
  head of International Member Relations\, Choksy is responsible for membe
 r services across all the U.S. Chamber's companies that are part of its I
 nternational Division.</p><p>  As senior vice president of the Middle Eas
 t and T├╝rkiye Department\, Choksy's responsibilities include oversight o
 f several bilateral business councils and programs. Under his leadership\
 , the Middle East portfolio has expanded to become the U.S. Chamber's lar
 gest international program and represents over 250 companies. Choksy also
  led the effort to integrate the U.S.-India Business Council into the U.S
 . Chamber.</p><p>  Before joining the Chamber\, Choksy was a director at 
 Chemonics International. There\, he led teams developing economic ties be
 tween the United States and the Middle East. He lived and worked in Jorda
 n for seven years\, and also lived and worked in India\, Sri Lanka\, and 
 the U.K. Prior to that\, Choksy worked for the Parsons Corporation. He is
  a recognized thought leader on the role of international business in the
  global economy.</p><p>  Choksy received his M.B.A. in strategic manageme
 nt from the Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania and his B.A.
 \, magna cum laude\, from Hamilton College. He lives with his wife and da
 ughter in Chevy Chase\, Maryland.</p>
