SUMMARY:Off-the-Record Dinner on Careers in Intelligence & National Secur
 ity
DESCRIPTION:What does it actually take to build a career in intelligence 
 or the White House?  Join a small\, off-the-record dinner with Judd Dever
 mont\, former National Intelligence Officer and senior National Security 
 Council official who helped shape U.S. policy at the highest levels of go
 vernment.This is not a speech. It is a direct conversation.  He has worke
 d inside the intelligence community\, coordinated across agencies\, and a
 dvised senior decision-makers on complex global crises. He has seen how p
 ower moves\, how policy is negotiated\, and how careers are built or stal
 led.We will talk about:      Breaking into intelligence and national secu
 rity          Moving between government\, analysis\, and policy roles    
       Negotiation and coalition building in real-world settings          
 The risks\, trade-offs\, and personal decisions behind public service    
       What early-career professionals get wrong      If you are serious a
 bout a future in intelligence\, national security\, or global affairs\, t
 his is a rare chance to ask unfiltered questions in a closed-door setting
 .Space is limited.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p data-start="518" data-end="598"><strong>W
 hat does it actually take to build a career in intelligence or the White 
 House?</strong></p><p data-start="600" data-end="791">  Join a small\, of
 f-the-record dinner with Judd Devermont\, former National Intelligence Of
 ficer and senior National Security Council official who helped shape U.S.
  policy at the highest levels of government.</p><p data-start="793" data-
 end="843"><strong>This is not a speech. It is a direct conversation.</str
 ong></p><p data-start="845" data-end="1076">  He has worked inside the in
 telligence community\, coordinated across agencies\, and advised senior d
 ecision-makers on complex global crises. He has seen how power moves\, ho
 w policy is negotiated\, and how careers are built or stalled.</p><p data
 -start="1078" data-end="1097"><strong>We will talk about:</strong></p><ul
  data-start="1099" data-end="1389"><li data-start="1099" data-end="1151">
 <p data-start="1101" data-end="1151">      Breaking into intelligence and
  national security    </p></li><li data-start="1152" data-end="1209"><p d
 ata-start="1154" data-end="1209">      Moving between government\, analys
 is\, and policy roles    </p></li><li data-start="1210" data-end="1271"><
 p data-start="1212" data-end="1271">      Negotiation and coalition build
 ing in real-world settings    </p></li><li data-start="1272" data-end="13
 43"><p data-start="1274" data-end="1343">      The risks\, trade-offs\, a
 nd personal decisions behind public service    </p></li><li data-start="1
 344" data-end="1389"><p data-start="1346" data-end="1389">      What earl
 y-career professionals get wrong    </p></li></ul><p data-start="1391" da
 ta-end="1555">  If you are serious about a future in intelligence\, natio
